CaseSummary.Summary: Vehicle one (V1 - case vehicle), a 2000 Honda Civic, 2-door coupe was traveling north in the northbound through-lane of a three-lane, two-way urban road and was approaching a four-leg intersection. Vehicle two (V2), a 2002 Ford Explorer (unknown specific type) was traveling west in the westbound through-lane of the intersecting three-lane, two-way road and was approaching the same intersection as V1. It was dark, there were no streetlights, the weather was clear, and the bituminous road was dry. Both vehicles entered the intersection at the same time and the front of V2 struck the right side of V1 in a T-type configuration. There was no physical evidence to substantiate the final resting positions of either vehicle nor were there any police markings. Both vehicles were towed, reportedly due to disabling vehicle damage. The 17-year-old female driver of V1 was using the available three-point seat belt but no air bags deployed. She was transported to a local hospital via ground ambulance (ISS-1) where she was treated and released. The 17-year-old female right-front passenger of V1 (case occupant) was also using the available three-point seat belt but no air bags deployed. She was transported via ground ambulance to a regional level-one trauma center.

CirenCaseForm.InjuryAnalysis:
The case occupant is the 163 cm (5 ft 4 in), 62 kg (136 lb) 17-year-old female right-front passenger of a 2000 Honda Civic, 2-door coupe. The case vehicle was struck in the right side by the front of a 2002 Ford Explorer while it was passing through a four-leg intersection. The impact was classified as severe. The WinSmash reconstruction program calculated a delta-v of 48 kmph (29 mph), which appeared to be consistent with the observed damage. The case occupant was using the available three-point seat belt. No air bags deployed.
She moved laterally to her right and slightly forward in response to the 2 o'clock direction of impact force (+70 degrees). She sustained a loss of consciousness possibly from contact with the beltline of the right-front door panel. She also sustained several pelvic and leg injuries from contact with the interior door panel including a right sacrum fracture, right anterior acetabulum fracture, bilateral superior and inferior pubic rami fractures, a right iliac wing fracture, and a right mid-shaft tibia fracture. Rate of door intrusion, amount of intrusion and contact with the raised center console may be contributing factors to her pelvic injuries.
